{
  "doc_id": "38134",
  "text": "In general, the interplay between bottom-up and top-down mechanisms mediates ASA. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] The separation between simultaneous sound events is based on numerous acoustic properties such as spectral, temporal, and spatial cues (bottom-up mechanisms). [CITATION_3] Also, stream segregation is a dynamic process that is modulated cognitively by top-down mechanisms, which involve the organization of acoustic components into perceptual object representations based on prior experiences [CITATION_4] or executive processes (especially working memory capacity and attention). Working memory capacity is defined as the ability to retain and manipulate information. Because speech perception requires the individual to follow, retain, and integrate a stream of auditory information, working memory capacity is likely to be a core component of speech perception.",
